[There is no information about the location, the eco-epidemiological scenarios where the infected monkeys were identified. Wild? Periurban? Urban? Have entomological investigations been carried out? Have active searches been carried out for suspected human cases? Was barrier vaccination performed?

Concerning the potential number of susceptible people, especially since it is a state where vaccination has been recommended for years and years, the challenge will be to organize vaccination actions in a short time for more than 200 000 people in a scenario in which gatherings are not recommended.

Unfortunately, very unfortunately, it will come as no surprise should human case(s) occur. - Mod. RNA]

[The dead monkeys indicate that the virus has been circulating in the state again. It is important that the human population yellow fever [YF] vaccination coverage reach the 95% goal set by the Ministry of Health. Vaccination is the only way to avoid these sylvan (forest) cases, since elimination of the forest YF virus transmission cycle is not feasible. Without prevention of any resulting human sylvan cases, there is the risk that YF virus could be introduced by them into the urban cycle of virus transmitted by _Aedes aegypti_ and spread quickly.

Occurrence of fatality in non-human primates raises concern for public health and also about potential conservation problems for some endangered or threatened primate species such as brown howler monkeys and golden lion tamarins. The above report does not indicate which species of monkeys died. There is no orally administered vaccine available to vaccinate non-human primates in the wild. - Mod.TY

